Additional tests on commit c50aeda have highlighted an additional issue.

The issue was related to the fact that everything is inserted in the ``definitions`` JSON object, which lead to a correct JSON representation which unfortunately is not respecting all the Swagger Specifications.

For example the following JSON is not valid Swagger:
```JSON
{
  "info": {
    "version": "1.0.0",
    "title": "title"
  },
  "paths": {
    "/test1/": {
      "$ref": "#/definitions/file.paths.json|..paths..test1"
    }
  },
  "schemes": [
    "http"
  ],
  "produces": [
    "application/json"
  ],
  "basePath": "/",
  "definitions": {
    "file.paths.json|..paths..test1": {
      "get": {
        "operationId": "test1",
        "responses": {
          "200": {
            "description": "Return integer",
            "schema": {
              "type": "integer"
            }
          }
        }
      }
    }
  },
  "swagger": "2.0"
}
```

In order to avoid it we need to dereference the [Path Item Object](https://github.com/OAI/OpenAPI-Specification/blob/master/versions/2.0.md#pathItemObject)s and to insert into the definitions the [Parameter Object](https://github.com/OAI/OpenAPI-Specification/blob/master/versions/2.0.md#parameterObject)s and [Reference Object](https://github.com/OAI/OpenAPI-Specification/blob/master/versions/2.0.md#referenceObject)s. The discrimination is provided by the ``_is_model_definition`` function.

