@OddBloke thanks for the PR and the relevant documentation.  Ideally this wouldn't even be falling back to the backup python but for whatever reason it is in your case.  I am not so sure it would be necessary to shellquote on windows-- we aren't shellquoting our [main which function](https://github.com/pypa/pipenv/blob/v9.0.1/pipenv/cli.py#L1431) which is used to look for python:

```python
    def which(command, location=None, allow_global=False):
        if location is None:
            location = project.virtualenv_location

        if not allow_global:
            if os.name == 'nt':
                p = find_windows_executable(os.path.join(location, 'Scripts'), command)
            else:
                p = os.sep.join([location] + ['bin/{0}'.format(command)])
        else:
            if command == 'python':
                p = sys.executable

    return p
```

I've tried this on windows now with and without the shellquoting and it seems to work fine both ways so I'm under the impression that python escapes the representation of the executable properly when necessary (I even tried in cases where the executable path has spaces in it, both still work),

This looks good to me.

For now I've disabled coverage metrics on pypy3 which fixes the problem. I don't think it's a major problem because the other Python 3.x tests should be hitting all the same lines anyway.

I think coverage is also causing some signfiicant slowdown in the `pypy` build, but not actually *failing*, so I left that in.

