@rearmstr - in case helpful, I sat down this morning and tried to remind myself what the "right" answer is for an elliptical Gaussian with an adaptive circular Gaussian weight function, so you can use that in code tests.  If you start with an elliptical Gaussian that has `sigma_x = sqrt(q) sigma` and `sigma_y = sigma / sqrt(q)` (so that the axis ratio is q), then with elliptical adaptive weights you should get the usual `|e| = (1-q^2) / (1+q^2)` when defining `e` using the `(Mxx-Myy)/(Mxx+Myy)` and `2 Mxy/(Mxx+Myy)` definition of shape.  If you make the weight function a circular Gaussian with that same `sigma` as above (which would happen when doing adaptive circular moments) then I believe you should get `|e| = (1-q^2) / (1 + q^2 + 2q)`.  So it's nearly the same answer except for that extra 2q in the denominator, .

I think that if you make circular Gaussians and shear them with axis ratio `q`, you should be able to use the above formula to test that the code I suggested above is correctly giving you e1 and e2.

